<subSubSection pageId="166" pageNumber="167" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="166" pageNumber="167">
Shrub to small tree 2-3.5 m tall with terete, caducously furfurate-lepidote branches; the nodal line not evident. Leaves of a pair somewhat unequal in size. Petiole 0.4-1.3 cm. Leaf blade 11-14 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2.5-5.2 cm, 3-5 plinerved with the innermost pair of lateral veins arising about 1-2 cm above the base and usually diverging from each other at their point of origin, elliptic, cuneate, apex caudate-acuminate, the margin entire, pocket like domatia present at the base abaxially on both pairs of lateral veins, adaxially glabrous, abaxially glabrous or caducously lepidote. Inflorescence an cyme axillary cyme 1.8-3.2 cm long, divaricately branched form the base with slender branches, accessory branches absent, the rachis inconspicuously furfurate-lepidote, bracteoles 2.2-5 cm long, triangular to subulate and fused basally to forma a peristent, shallow amplexicaul collar, 1-1.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-1 mm, persistent. Flowers sessile or subsessile, 4 (-5) merous, not calyptrate nor with the calyx lobes fused in bud, the hypanthium 2.25-2.75 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.75-2.25 mm, glabrous, calyx lobes broadly triangular ovate, 0.5-1 mm long, calyx teeth subulate, 0.5 mm long. Immature petals 1.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.2 mm, triangular ovate, posture not seen live at anthesis, glabrous, apically broadly acute. Stamens not studied, reportedly 8 (-10) in number. Ovary 4 (-5) locular, inferior. Style ca. 5 mm long, not observed in good flower at anthesis. Berry 4-5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-5 mm, dark purple to black. Seeds 0.4-0.6 mm long, more or less triangular in outline, the testa muriculate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="167" lastPageNumber="168" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="166" pageNumber="167">
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 153" captionStartId="F153" captionText="Figure 153. Distribution of Conostegia ecuadorensis." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure153" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96511" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">153</figureCitation>
). On the Pacific slope of Colombia and north western Ecuador with a population on the eastern side of the Andes in Ecuador, 100-2000 m in elevation.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="973957" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.67.6703.figure153" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/96511" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" start="Figure 153" startId="F153">
<paragraph pageId="166" pageNumber="167">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Figure 153.</emphasis>
Distribution of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ecuadorensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph lastPageId="167" lastPageNumber="168" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ecuadorensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by its mostly glabrous vegetative parts, its caudate leaf apex forming a long drip tip, the presence four pocket domatia at the base of the leaf on the abaxial side where each of the major lateral veins arises, and its 4-merous flowers on divaricately branched slender inflorescences branches. Gleason described 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ecuadorensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the same year that he described 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ombrophila" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ombrophila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ombrophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gleason, HA" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="241" pageNumber="242" pagination="97 - 140" publicationUrl="10.2307/2804810" refId="B31" refString="Gleason, HA, 1939a. The genus Clidemia in Mexico and Central America. Brittonia 3 (2): 97 - 140, DOI: 10.2307/2804810" title="The genus Clidemia in Mexico and Central America." url="10.2307/2804810" volume="3" year="1939 a">Gleason 1939a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gleason, HA" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club" pageId="241" pageNumber="242" pagination="415 - 419" publicationUrl="10.2307/2481041" refId="B32" refString="Gleason, HA, 1939b. Eight undescribed species of Melastomataceae. Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club 66: 415 - 419, DOI: 10.2307/2481041" title="Eight undescribed species of Melastomataceae." url="10.2307/2481041" volume="66" year="1939 b">b</bibRefCitation>
). These two species are quite similar in their almost glabrous vegetative parts with inconspicuous lepidote hairs, presence of leaf domatia, and caudate leaf apices, so it is surprising he did not comment on the similarities between the two. In fact, they can be hard to separate, with 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ecuadorensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having four domatia and a more southern distribution, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ombrophila" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ombrophila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ombrophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
none or usually two domatia and a more southern Central American distribution. Instead, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gleason, HA" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club" pageId="241" pageNumber="242" pagination="415 - 419" publicationUrl="10.2307/2481041" refId="B32" refString="Gleason, HA, 1939b. Eight undescribed species of Melastomataceae. Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club 66: 415 - 419, DOI: 10.2307/2481041" title="Eight undescribed species of Melastomataceae." url="10.2307/2481041" volume="66" year="1939 b">Gleason (1939b)</bibRefCitation>
compared 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ecuadorensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authority="D.Don, 1823" authorityName="D.Don" authorityYear="1823" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomaceae" genus="Clidemia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Clidemia japurensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japurensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Clidemia japurensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="D.Don, 1823" authorityName="D.Don" authorityYear="1823" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomaceae" genus="Clidemia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Clidemia naevula" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="naevula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Clidemia naevula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(now considered a synonym of the 
<taxonomicName authority="D.Don, 1823" authorityName="D.Don" authorityYear="1823" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomaceae" genus="Clidemia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Clidemia japurensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="japurensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Clidemia japurensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) of section 
<taxonomicName authority="D.Don, 1823" authorityName="D.Don" authorityYear="1823" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomaceae" genus="Clidemia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Staphidium">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Staphidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(where he placed, 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ecuadorensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), two glandular pubescent species that we know now, are distantly related from 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ecuadorensis" order="Myrtales" pageId="166" pageNumber="167" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ecuadorensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="166" pageNumber="167">Conostegia ecuadorensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on molecular phylogenies. 
<pageBreakToken pageId="167" pageNumber="168" start="start">On</pageBreakToken>
the other hand, he did not place 
<taxonomicName authority="Kriebel, 2016" authorityName="Kriebel" authorityYear="2016" baseAuthorityName="Gleason" baseAuthorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Conostegia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Conostegia ombrophila" order="Myrtales" pageId="167" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ombrophila">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="167" pageNumber="168">Conostegia ombrophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in any section or compare to any other species, stating that its position in 
<taxonomicName authority="D.Don, 1823" authorityName="D.Don" authorityYear="1823" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomaceae" genus="Clidemia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Clidemia" order="Myrtales" pageId="167" pageNumber="168" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="167" pageNumber="168">Clidemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was uncertain.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
